# Java Spring Boot Standards (your monorepo)

Apply these standards when writing or modifying Java/Spring Boot code in this workspace
(Agentic Loop / your service services and related APIs). Patterns are derived from the
`SpringBootProdTemplate` reference and existing Agentic Loop services.

**Toolchain baseline:** Java 25 (Corretto), Spring Boot 4.x, Gradle 9.x.
Do NOT add explicit version pins — the BOM/platform manages versions.

## 1. Architecture & layering
Controller -> Orchestration service -> granular services -> repository/client. Keep
controllers thin (no business logic). Program to interfaces.

- Each service has an interface (`IFooService`) and an impl (`impl/FooService`).
- Inject collaborators via constructor with `@RequiredArgsConstructor`. Never use field `@Autowired`.
- **No try-catch or Azure/external SDK calls inside controllers.** Move all I/O to the service layer and let exceptions surface to `GlobalExceptionHandler`.
- **Centralize domain not-found handling in the service layer** — controllers must not repeat `orElseThrow(() -> new EntityNotFoundException(...))`. See §7 *Service-layer not-found and Optional lookups*.

```java
// GOOD
@Service
@RequiredArgsConstructor
@Slf4j
public class FooOrchestrationService implements IFooOrchestrationService {
    private final ICreateFooService createFooService;
    private final IFooRetrievalService fooRetrievalService;
}

// BAD
@Service
public class FooService {
    @Autowired private CreateFooService createFooService; // field injection, concrete type
}
```

## 2. Java 25 language features — prefer modern syntax

Actively use Java 25 constructs instead of verbose equivalents:

- **Records** for all immutable value types, DTOs, config holders, internal results:
  ```java
  public record ErrorDetail(String field, String message) { }
  public record CellHealthSummary(String cellId, String status, Instant checkedAt) { }
  ```
- **Sealed classes** for closed domain hierarchies (e.g. health check result variants):
  ```java
  public sealed interface CheckResult permits OkResult, DegradedResult, DownResult { }
  ```
- **Pattern matching for `instanceof`** — no explicit cast:
  ```java
  // GOOD
  if (result instanceof DegradedResult dr) { log.warn("Degraded: {}", dr.reason()); }
  // BAD
  if (result instanceof DegradedResult) { DegradedResult dr = (DegradedResult) result; }
  ```
- **Pattern matching for `switch`** (finalized):
  ```java
  String label = switch (result) {
      case OkResult ok      -> "UP";
      case DegradedResult d -> "DEGRADED: " + d.reason();
      case DownResult dn    -> "DOWN";
  };
  ```
- **Text blocks** for multi-line strings (JSON templates, SQL, YAML snippets):
  ```java
  String body = """
      {"cellId": "%s", "status": "DOWN"}
      """.formatted(cellId);
  ```
- **`var`** for local variables where the type is obvious from the right-hand side. Do not use `var` for fields or where it obscures the type.
- **Virtual threads** — Spring Boot 4 enables virtual threads by default (`spring.threads.virtual.enabled=true`). Do NOT create raw `Thread` objects or tune thread-pool sizes for I/O-bound work; let the container manage concurrency.

## 3. Boilerplate reduction (Lombok / records / MapStruct)
- DTOs & entities: Lombok (`@Data`, `@Builder`, `@NoArgsConstructor`, `@AllArgsConstructor`;
  `@SuperBuilder` + `@EqualsAndHashCode(callSuper = true)` for inheritance).
- Prefer Java `record` over Lombok for immutable types — records are a first-class Java 25 feature.
- Entity <-> DTO mapping: MapStruct `@Mapper` interfaces. For simple single/list mapping use a shared `DtoConverter`.
- Never hand-write getters/setters/equals/hashCode/builders/mappers.

```java
// GOOD - prefer record for immutable value type
public record ErrorDetail(String field, String message) { }

// GOOD - MapStruct
@Mapper
public interface FooMapper {
    FooResponseDTO toResponseDTO(FooEntity entity);
}

// GOOD - MapStruct variant (no multi-arg record constructors in services)
@Mapping(target = "status", expression = "java(stale ? HealthStatus.STALE : snapshot.status())")
CellSnapshotDTO withComputedStaleness(CellSnapshotDTO snapshot, String staleness, boolean stale);

// BAD - service-layer 10+ arg record constructor
return new CellSnapshotDTO(snapshot.cellId(), snapshot.environment(), ...);
```

Additional rules (your service PR review learnings):
- **No multi-arg record constructors in services** — use MapStruct `@Mapping` variant methods.
- **Records do not need `@Builder`** when MapStruct owns construction.
- **No inline FQCN** in mapper interfaces — import types normally.
- **Component health rows:** `CellComponentStatusDTO` + `CellComponent` enum (`@JsonValue wireName()`), not `SubsystemStatusDTO` + string literals.
- **Injected mapper fields** must be descriptive: `cellHealthEventMapper`, not `mapper`.

## 4. Apache Commons — mandatory for null/empty/blank checks

Use Apache Commons (`org.apache.commons.lang3.StringUtils`, `org.apache.commons.lang3.ArrayUtils`,
`org.apache.commons.collections4.CollectionUtils`) or Spring `StringUtils.hasText`.
**Never write manual null/blank/empty checks — this is a code review failure.**

```java
// GOOD
if (StringUtils.isBlank(correlationId)) { correlationId = UUID.randomUUID().toString(); }
if (CollectionUtils.isNotEmpty(errors)) { builder.errors(errors); }
if (ArrayUtils.isEmpty(originalArgs)) { return new Object[0]; }

// BAD — banned patterns
if (correlationId == null || correlationId.isBlank()) { ... }        // use StringUtils.isBlank
if (name == null || name.trim().isEmpty()) { ... }                   // use StringUtils.isBlank
if (errors != null && !errors.isEmpty()) { ... }                     // use CollectionUtils.isNotEmpty
if (originalArgs == null || originalArgs.length == 0) { ... }       // use ArrayUtils.isEmpty
```

Apache Commons is already on the classpath transitively; import from:
- `org.apache.commons.lang3.StringUtils`
- `org.apache.commons.lang3.ArrayUtils`
- `org.apache.commons.collections4.CollectionUtils`
- `org.apache.commons.collections4.MapUtils`

## 5. Validation (Bean Validation + custom annotations)
- Validate request DTOs with standard constraints (`@NotBlank`, `@Size`, `@Email`, `@Min`).
- **Never do manual null/blank checks in controllers.** Declare constraints on the DTO and annotate the controller parameter with `@Valid`.
- Extract reusable/business rules into a **custom annotation** (`@Constraint(validatedBy = ...)`) backed by a `ConstraintValidator` — declare once, reuse everywhere.
- Controllers trigger validation with `@Valid` (body) and `@Validated` (class for params).
- Constraint `message` MUST be a property key in braces, never an inline literal.

```java
// GOOD - reusable custom constraint
@Documented
@Constraint(validatedBy = CountryCodeValidator.class)
@Target({ElementType.FIELD, ElementType.PARAMETER})
@Retention(RetentionPolicy.RUNTIME)
public @interface ValidCountryCode {
    String message() default "{account.countryCode.invalid}";
    Class<?>[] groups() default {};
    Class<? extends Payload>[] payload() default {};
}

// GOOD - DTO usage
@NotBlank(message = "{account.name.notblank}")
@Size(min = 1, max = 255, message = "{account.name.size}")
private String accountName;

// BAD - manual check + inline literal in controller
if (name == null || name.trim().isEmpty()) {
    return ResponseEntity.badRequest().body("Name cannot be empty");
}
```

## 6. i18n & messages
- All validation/error/user-facing strings live in resource bundles, never hardcoded in code:
  - `ValidationMessages.properties` — constraint messages.
  - `i18n/messages.properties` (+ locale variants like `messages_en.properties`) — business/error messages.
- Resolve messages via a `MessageSource`-backed `Translator` helper (with US fallback).
- Key naming: `module.field.constraint` (e.g. `account.email.size`) and `error.<domain>.<case>`
  (e.g. `error.account.notFound`). Placeholders use numeric indices `{0}`, `{1}`.
- Error message keys must be centralized in a `constants/ErrorMessageConstants.java` final class.

```java
// GOOD
String msg = Translator.getMessage(ErrorMessageConstants.ERROR_INTERNAL_SERVER);
String msg = Translator.getMessage("error.account.notFound", accountId);

// BAD
String msg = "Account not found with ID: " + accountId;
String msg = Translator.getMessage("error.account.notFound");  // literal key inline
```

## 7. Error handling
One `@RestControllerAdvice GlobalExceptionHandler` per service. Map every exception to a
consistent `ApiErrorResponseDTO` (`timestamp`, `status`, `message`, `errors`) built via
`ExceptionUtils`. **Never return `ResponseEntity<String>` from an exception handler.**

Required handlers (in order):
1. `MethodArgumentNotValidException` → 400 + field `errors` map
2. `HttpMessageNotReadableException`, `MethodArgumentTypeMismatchException` → 400
3. `IllegalArgumentException` → 400 (generic i18n message; do NOT echo `ex.getMessage()`)
4. `AuthorizationDeniedException` → 403 (generic i18n; log server-side only)
5. `NoResourceFoundException` → 404
6. `Exception` → 500 catch-all (log full exception; return generic i18n message)

**Never leak `ex.getMessage()` or stack traces to clients.** Log server-side; return i18n keys.

Timestamp format must be deterministic — use `DateTimeFormatter.ISO_OFFSET_DATE_TIME`:
```java
.timestamp(OffsetDateTime.now().format(DateTimeFormatter.ISO_OFFSET_DATE_TIME))
```

```java
@Slf4j
@RestControllerAdvice
public class GlobalExceptionHandler {

    @ExceptionHandler(MethodArgumentNotValidException.class)
    public ResponseEntity<ApiErrorResponseDTO> handleValidation(MethodArgumentNotValidException ex) {
        log.warn("Validation error: {}", ex.getMessage());
        Map<String, String> errors = ExceptionUtils.processValidationErrors(
            ex.getBindingResult().getAllErrors().toArray(new ObjectError[0]));
        return ResponseEntity.badRequest().body(
            ExceptionUtils.buildErrorResponse(HttpStatus.BAD_REQUEST,
                Translator.getMessage(ErrorMessageConstants.ERROR_VALIDATION_FAILED), errors));
    }

    @ExceptionHandler(Exception.class)
    public ResponseEntity<ApiErrorResponseDTO> handleAll(Exception ex) {
        log.error("Unhandled exception", ex);   // full trace server-side only
        return ResponseEntity.status(HttpStatus.INTERNAL_SERVER_ERROR).body(
            ExceptionUtils.buildErrorResponse(HttpStatus.INTERNAL_SERVER_ERROR,
                Translator.getMessage(ErrorMessageConstants.ERROR_INTERNAL_SERVER), null));
    }
}
```

Add `@JsonInclude(JsonInclude.Include.NON_NULL)` on `ApiErrorResponseDTO` so the `errors` field
is omitted from the JSON when absent (not serialized as `null`).

### Service-layer not-found and Optional lookups

**Bottom line:** Centralizing exceptions in the service layer is good practice in this codebase.
Controllers stay lean — delegate and return `ResponseEntity.ok(...)`; do not scatter
`orElseThrow(() -> new EntityNotFoundException(...))` across controllers.

When a lookup can **miss** and callers disagree on whether miss means error (404 endpoint) vs
normal control flow (fallback path, negative cache), expose **two service methods** — same pattern
as Spring Data `findById` vs `getById`:

| Method | Returns | Use when |
|--------|---------|----------|
| `findX(...)` | `Optional<X>` | Composition, cache-friendly lookup, miss is not always an error |
| `requireX(...)` / `readXById(...)` | `X` (throws `EntityNotFoundException`) | Callers that require a document; **not** `@Cacheable` itself |

The throwing wrapper delegates to the cached `find*` method so negative caching still works.
**Never throw inside `@Cacheable`** — exceptions bypass cache population and defeat negative-cache
goals (see Agentic Loop assignments `findAltId` / `requireAltId` pattern).

```java
// GOOD — cached lookup + service-layer throw (controller stays thin)
@Cacheable(value = "altIds", key = "#entityType + '-' + #id")
public Optional<AltId> findAltId(String id, CellEntityType entityType) {
    return altIdRepository.findById(id, partitionKey(id, entityType));
}

public AltId requireAltId(String id, CellEntityType entityType) {
    return findAltId(id, entityType)
            .orElseThrow(() -> new EntityNotFoundException(entityType, AltId.class));
}

// Controller — no orElseThrow duplication
return ResponseEntity.ok(altIdService.requireAltId(id, entityType));
```

```java
// BAD — repeated orElseThrow in every controller
return ResponseEntity.ok(altIdService.findAltId(id, entityType)
        .orElseThrow(() -> new EntityNotFoundException(entityType, AltId.class)));

// BAD — throw inside @Cacheable (misses not negative-cached)
@Cacheable(value = "altIds", key = "#entityType + '-' + #id")
public AltId readAltIdByIdAndEntityType(String id, CellEntityType entityType, Class<?> type) {
    return altIdRepository.findById(id, partitionKey(id, entityType))
            .orElseThrow(() -> new EntityNotFoundException(entityType, type));
}

// BAD — ResponseEntity.of(optional) when ApiErrorResponseDTO shape is required
return ResponseEntity.of(altIdService.findAltId(id, entityType));  // 404 skips GlobalExceptionHandler
```

**Spring AOP note:** `require*` must call `find*` through the Spring proxy (separate bean,
`@Lazy` self-injection, or facade). Same-class `this.find*()` bypasses `@Cacheable`.

Domain exceptions (`EntityNotFoundException`, `BadRequestException`, etc.) are thrown in the
service layer; `GlobalExceptionHandler` maps them to HTTP status and `ApiErrorResponseDTO`.

## 8. Constants & enums (no magic values)
- `final` utility/constant classes with a private constructor.
- Centralize API endpoints, HTTP headers, DB column names, error message keys, and MDC keys.
- All string literals that appear more than once MUST be in a constants class.
- Use enums for fixed value sets (status, prefixes).
- **`ApiConstants` must cover every path segment**, including nested routes (`EVENTS = "/events"`, `EVENT_STREAM = "/stream"`). Compose controller mappings from constants only.
- **Domain enums** for fixed component/status sets (`CellComponent`, `HealthStatus`); probe and event payloads reference enums, not free-form strings.

```java
public final class CommonConstants {
    private CommonConstants() { }
    public static final String API_V1_PREFIX = "/api/v1";
    public static final String IDEMPOTENCY_KEY_HEADER = "Idempotency-Key";
    public static final String CORRELATION_ID_HEADER = "X-Correlation-Id";
    public static final String MDC_CORRELATION_KEY = "correlationId";
}

public final class ErrorMessageConstants {
    private ErrorMessageConstants() { }
    public static final String ERROR_INTERNAL_SERVER  = "error.internal.server";
    public static final String ERROR_ACCESS_DENIED    = "error.access.denied";
    public static final String ERROR_BAD_REQUEST      = "error.bad.request";
    public static final String ERROR_VALIDATION_FAILED = "error.validation.failed";
    public static final String ERROR_RESOURCE_NOT_FOUND = "error.resource.notFound";
}
```

## 9. REST / API conventions
- Build `@RequestMapping` paths from constants; return `ResponseEntity<T>`.
- Document every endpoint with OpenAPI annotations (`@Tag`, `@Operation`, `@ApiResponses`).
- **Error response schemas must appear in `@ApiResponse` annotations** using `@Content(schema = @Schema(implementation = ApiErrorResponseDTO.class))`.
- Idempotency via an `Idempotency-Key` header is the pattern for create/update where needed (optional).
- **Validate correlation ID from incoming headers** — accept only if it matches UUID format or a bounded length/charset; otherwise generate a new one. Use `StringUtils.isBlank()` for the absent check.

```java
// GOOD - OpenAPI with error schema
@Operation(summary = "Create foo")
@ApiResponses({
    @ApiResponse(responseCode = "201", description = "Created"),
    @ApiResponse(responseCode = "400", description = "Validation failed",
        content = @Content(schema = @Schema(implementation = ApiErrorResponseDTO.class))),
    @ApiResponse(responseCode = "500", description = "Internal error",
        content = @Content(schema = @Schema(implementation = ApiErrorResponseDTO.class)))
})
```

## 10. Configuration & cross-cutting concerns
- Prefer record-based `@ConfigurationProperties` over scattered `@Value` for typed config.
- Use a shared `RestClient` bean with explicit connect/read timeouts. Never `new RestTemplate()` per call.
- Resilience: Spring-native `@EnableResilientMethods` on the app class + `@Retryable` on outbound calls. Do not add Resilience4j unless a feature requires circuit-breaking.
- Add a `CorrelationIdFilter` that puts `X-Correlation-Id` into the SLF4J MDC.
- **Virtual threads** — confirm `spring.threads.virtual.enabled=true` in `application.yml`. Do not configure raw Tomcat/Jetty thread-pool sizes for I/O-bound services under Spring Boot 4.

```java
@Configuration
public class RestClientConfig {
    @Bean
    public RestClient restClient(
            @Value("${app.rest-connect-timeout-ms:5000}") int connectMs,
            @Value("${app.rest-read-timeout-ms:10000}") int readMs) {
        var factory = new SimpleClientHttpRequestFactory();
        factory.setConnectTimeout(connectMs);
        factory.setReadTimeout(readMs);
        return RestClient.builder().requestFactory(factory).build();
    }
}

// Record-based config (preferred over @Value fields)
@ConfigurationProperties(prefix = "cdp.health")
public record HealthConfig(int aggregatorTimeoutMs, String centralBaseUrl) { }

// GOOD - yaml drives @Scheduled; constant drives @DefaultValue only
@Scheduled(fixedDelayString = "${cdp.health.publisher.heartbeat-interval-ms:15000}")
public void publishHeartbeat() { ... }

public record PublisherProperties(
    @DefaultValue(CellHealthConstants.DEFAULT_HEARTBEAT_INTERVAL_MS) int heartbeatIntervalMs) {}
```

Additional rules:
- **`application.yml` holds operational defaults**; `@ConfigurationProperties` records reference `*Constants` for `@DefaultValue`, not duplicate magic numbers in Java and yaml.
- **One `RestClient` bean** per service from `RestClientProperties` — do not create a second ad-hoc bean in another `@Configuration` class.
- **`@Qualifier` + named constant** when injecting `List<Interface>` beans that have wrapper variants (e.g. `OBSERVED_HEALTH_PROBES`).

### Caching (your service / Agentic Loop pattern)
- Enable Spring Cache once per app: `@EnableCaching` on the `@SpringBootApplication` class.
- Configure Caffeine via yaml only: `spring.cache.type: caffeine` + `spring.cache.caffeine.spec` (e.g. `maximumSize=100,expireAfterWrite=30s`). Do **not** duplicate TTL in Java builders.
- **All application caching flows through `CellHealthCacheService`** (or repo-specific `*CacheService`) using `@Cacheable(sync=true)` on read methods and `@CacheEvict` / `@Caching` on writes. Controllers, inventory services, event processors, and repositories **delegate** — they do not carry `@Cacheable`.
- Cache names live in `CellHealthConstants` (e.g. `CACHE_CELL_SNAPSHOTS`, `CACHE_HEALTHZ_ROLLUP`).
- Evict affected keys **before** SSE broadcast or downstream publish so clients never see stale post-write data.
- Do **not** cache DTOs with computed staleness — cache raw snapshots; apply staleness after cache hit in the service layer.
- SSE connection tables belong in a dedicated `SseEmitterRegistry` `@Component`, not on domain services.

```java
@Service
@RequiredArgsConstructor
public class CellHealthCacheService implements ICellHealthCacheService {
    private final ICellSnapshotRepository repository;

    @Cacheable(value = CellHealthConstants.CACHE_CELL_SNAPSHOTS, key = "#cellId", sync = true)
    public Optional<CellSnapshotDTO> getRawCell(String cellId) {
        return repository.findByCellId(cellId);
    }

    @CacheEvict(value = {CellHealthConstants.CACHE_CELL_SNAPSHOTS, CellHealthConstants.CACHE_CELL_LIST}, allEntries = true)
    public void evictAll() { }
}
```

## 11. Persistence
- your monorepo services use Azure Cosmos DB (Spring Data Cosmos) for persistence and
  Event Hub (Spring Cloud Stream / StreamBridge) for messaging.
- For relational data, use the JPA `Specification` dynamic-filter pattern with
  `JpaSpecificationExecutor`, a `BaseEntity` for audit fields, and field-name constants
  (no hardcoded property strings in predicates).

## 12. Logging
- Use SLF4J via Lombok `@Slf4j`. Always parameterize; never concatenate strings; never `printStackTrace()`.
- **Never log sensitive data** (tokens, credentials, PII).
- **Never log `ex.getMessage()` at WARN/ERROR if the value flows from user input** — a full exception at ERROR is fine since it stays server-side.

```java
log.info("Created account {}", accountId);     // GOOD
log.error("Unhandled exception", ex);          // GOOD - full exception, server-side
log.info("Created account " + accountId);      // BAD - concatenation
log.warn("Error: {}", ex.getMessage());        // BAD - may leak user-controlled input
```

## 13. Testing & quality — framework versions & mandatory patterns

**Exact versions on the classpath (Spring Boot 4.0.6 BOM):**
- JUnit **6.0.3** (major new version — not 5!)
- Mockito **5.20.0**
- AssertJ **3.27.7**
- Spring Security Test **7.0.5**
- Spring Test **7.0.7**

### 13a. Unit tests — JUnit 6 + Mockito 5 + AssertJ

**`@MockBean`/`@SpyBean` are removed in Spring Boot 4.** Use `@MockitoBean`/`@MockitoSpyBean` only in
Spring-context tests. For pure unit tests use `@ExtendWith(MockitoExtension.class)`.

In Spring Boot 4, `MockitoTestExecutionListener` is **not** auto-registered — **always add
`@ExtendWith(MockitoExtension.class)` explicitly** to unit test classes.

```java
// GOOD — pure unit test
@ExtendWith(MockitoExtension.class)
class CellHealthAggregatorTest {

    @Mock
    private ICellHealthProbeService probeService;

    @InjectMocks
    private CellHealthAggregatorService aggregator;

    @Captor
    ArgumentCaptor<String> cellIdCaptor;

    @Test
    @DisplayName("given critical dependency DOWN, aggregation result is DOWN")
    void givenCriticalDepDown_whenAggregate_thenResultIsDown() {
        when(probeService.probe("cosmos")).thenReturn(CheckResult.DOWN);

        var result = aggregator.aggregate("cell-01");

        assertThat(result.status()).isEqualTo("DOWN");
        verify(probeService).probe(cellIdCaptor.capture());
        assertThat(cellIdCaptor.getValue()).isEqualTo("cosmos");
    }
}
```

**Prefer AssertJ `assertThat` over JUnit `assertEquals`.** JUnit assertions are permitted but AssertJ
produces richer failure messages and chains fluently.

```java
// GOOD — AssertJ fluent, self-documenting failure message
assertThat(response.getBody())
    .isNotNull()
    .satisfies(body -> {
        assertThat(body.status()).isEqualTo(500);
        assertThat(body.timestamp()).isNotNull();
        assertThat(body.message()).doesNotContain("internal-secret");
    });

// GOOD — recursive comparison for DTOs (ignores auto-generated fields)
assertThat(actualDto)
    .usingRecursiveComparison()
    .ignoringFields("timestamp", "id")
    .isEqualTo(expectedDto);

// GOOD — soft assertions: collect ALL failures instead of stopping at first
SoftAssertions.assertSoftly(softly -> {
    softly.assertThat(response.status()).isEqualTo(400);
    softly.assertThat(response.message()).isNotBlank();
    softly.assertThat(response.errors()).containsKey("cellId");
});

// BAD
assertEquals(500, response.getBody().getStatus());  // short-circuits on fail, poor message
assertNull(response.getBody().getErrors());          // use assertThat(...).isNull()
```

**`@Nested` for behavior grouping — structure tests as Given/When/Then trees:**

```java
@ExtendWith(MockitoExtension.class)
class CellHealthRollupTest {

    @Nested
    @DisplayName("when all subsystems are healthy")
    class AllHealthy {
        @Test void healthzReturns200() { ... }
        @Test void statusPayloadShowsAllUp() { ... }
    }

    @Nested
    @DisplayName("when a critical dependency is down")
    class CriticalDown {
        @Test void healthzReturns503() { ... }
        @Test void failedSubsystemsListIsPopulated() { ... }
    }
}
```

**`@ParameterizedTest` for data-driven cases — avoid copy-paste:**

```java
@ParameterizedTest(name = "status={0} → httpCode={1}")
@CsvSource({"UP, 200", "DEGRADED, 200", "DOWN, 503"})
void healthzStatusMapsToCorrectHttpCode(String status, int expectedCode) {
    when(rollupService.compute()).thenReturn(new HealthRollup(status));
    assertThat(controller.healthz().getStatusCode().value()).isEqualTo(expectedCode);
}
```

**Mockito 5.20 — generic types in `MockedStatic`/`MockedConstruction` (no raw-type warnings):**

```java
// GOOD — typed generic mock (Mockito 5.20+)
try (MockedStatic<AzureResourceManager> mocked =
        Mockito.mockStatic(AzureResourceManager.class)) {
    mocked.when(() -> AzureResourceManager.authenticate(any(), any()))
          .thenReturn(authenticated);
    // ...
}

// BAD (pre-5.20 workaround no longer needed)
// MockedConstruction<MyGenericType> raw = mockConstruction(MyGenericType.class);
```

### 13b. Web-layer slice tests — `@WebMvcTest`

Use `org.springframework.boot.webmvc.test.autoconfigure.WebMvcTest` (new Spring Boot 4 package).
Use `@MockitoBean` (not `@MockBean` — removed in Boot 4).
`@SpringBootTest`/`MockMvc` tests must run filters to exercise `CorrelationIdFilter` and security.

```java
@WebMvcTest(CellHealthController.class)
@Import({SecurityConfig.class, GlobalExceptionHandler.class, MessageSourceConfig.class, Translator.class})
@AutoConfigureMockMvc
class CellHealthControllerTest {

    @Autowired MockMvc mockMvc;

    @MockitoBean  // NOT @MockBean — that annotation is removed in Boot 4
    ICellHealthAggregatorService aggregatorService;

    @Test
    @WithMockUser
    void whenAggregationFails_returns500WithApiErrorShape() throws Exception {
        when(aggregatorService.aggregate(any())).thenThrow(new RuntimeException("cosmos timeout"));

        mockMvc.perform(get("/my-service/v1/healthz"))
               .andExpect(status().isInternalServerError())
               .andExpect(content().contentType(MediaType.APPLICATION_JSON))
               .andExpect(jsonPath("$.status").value(500))
               .andExpect(jsonPath("$.timestamp").exists())
               .andExpect(jsonPath("$.message").exists())
               .andExpect(jsonPath("$.errors").doesNotExist()); // NON_NULL: absent, not null
    }

    @Test
    @WithMockUser
    void validationFailure_returns400WithFieldErrors() throws Exception {
        mockMvc.perform(post("/my-service/v1/status")
                        .content("{}")
                        .contentType(MediaType.APPLICATION_JSON))
               .andExpect(status().isBadRequest())
               .andExpect(jsonPath("$.errors").isMap());
    }

    @Test
    void unauthenticatedAccess_returns403() throws Exception {
        mockMvc.perform(get("/my-service/v1/healthz"))
               .andExpect(status().isForbidden());
    }
}
```

### 13c. Integration tests — `RestTestClient` (Spring Boot 4, replaces `TestRestTemplate`)

`TestRestTemplate` is deprecated. Use `RestTestClient` with `@AutoConfigureRestTestClient`:

```java
@SpringBootTest(webEnvironment = SpringBootTest.WebEnvironment.RANDOM_PORT)
@AutoConfigureRestTestClient
@Testcontainers
class CellHealthAggregatorIT {

    @Autowired
    RestTestClient restClient;

    @Test
    void actuatorHealthIsUp() {
        restClient.get()
                  .uri("/actuator/health")
                  .exchange()
                  .expectStatus().is2xxSuccessful()
                  .expectBody()
                  .jsonPath("$.status").isEqualTo("UP");
    }
}
```

### 13d. JaCoCo & coverage gates

- Keep the line coverage gate at **0.80**.
- Exclude `*Application.class`, `**/configuration/**`, `**/constants/**`, `**/dto/**`, `**/enum/**`
  from coverage measurement — these are config/structural, not logic.
- Measured packages (`controllers`, `services`, `util`, `i18n`) must genuinely exceed 0.80.
  Do not add exclusions to inflate the ratio artificially.

## 14. Test infrastructure — OOP patterns to eliminate duplication

### 14a. Abstract base test classes

Share Spring context, fixture setup, and common assertions via inheritance. This avoids repeating
`@Import`, `@TestPropertySource`, or `@WithMockUser` across every test class.

```java
// src/test/java/.../support/AbstractWebMvcTest.java
@WebMvcTest
@Import({SecurityConfig.class, GlobalExceptionHandler.class, MessageSourceConfig.class, Translator.class})
@AutoConfigureMockMvc
abstract class AbstractWebMvcTest {

    @Autowired
    protected MockMvc mockMvc;

    // Shared assertion helper — no duplication across concrete test classes
    protected void assertApiErrorShape(ResultActions result, int status) throws Exception {
        result.andExpect(content().contentType(MediaType.APPLICATION_JSON))
              .andExpect(jsonPath("$.status").value(status))
              .andExpect(jsonPath("$.timestamp").exists())
              .andExpect(jsonPath("$.message").exists());
    }
}

// Concrete test — inherits wiring, no repetition
@WebMvcTest(CellHealthController.class)
class CellHealthControllerTest extends AbstractWebMvcTest {

    @MockitoBean ICellHealthAggregatorService aggregatorService;

    @Test
    @WithMockUser
    void whenAggregationFails_returns500() throws Exception {
        when(aggregatorService.aggregate(any())).thenThrow(new RuntimeException());
        assertApiErrorShape(mockMvc.perform(get("/my-service/v1/healthz")), 500);
    }
}
```

### 14b. Test fixtures — record-based object mothers

Use Java records as factories for canonical test values. Avoids scattered magic strings and keeps
domain language in one place.

```java
// src/test/java/.../support/CellHealthFixtures.java
public final class CellHealthFixtures {
    private CellHealthFixtures() { }

    public static final String CELL_ID         = "cell-us-east-01";
    public static final String COSMOS_ENDPOINT = "https://cosmos-test.documents.azure.com";

    public static CellStatusDTO healthyCell() {
        return new CellStatusDTO(CELL_ID, "UP", List.of(), Instant.now());
    }

    public static CellStatusDTO degradedCell(String reason) {
        return new CellStatusDTO(CELL_ID, "DEGRADED", List.of(reason), Instant.now());
    }

    public static CellStatusDTO downCell() {
        return new CellStatusDTO(CELL_ID, "DOWN", List.of("cosmos", "eventhub"), Instant.now());
    }
}
```

### 14c. Testcontainers 2.0 — shared container via `@TestConfiguration`

Testcontainers **2.0** renamed all modules to `testcontainers-{name}` (e.g., `testcontainers-postgresql`).
Use `@ServiceConnection` to auto-wire properties — no manual `@DynamicPropertySource` needed.
Use a shared `@TestConfiguration` to start one container per test suite run:

```java
// Gradle: testImplementation("org.testcontainers:testcontainers-cosmosdb")
// For Azure Cosmos and Event Hub use WireMock or the Azure SDK emulator image

@TestConfiguration(proxyBeanMethods = false)
class TestInfraConfig {

    @Bean
    @ServiceConnection               // auto-wires spring.data.* properties
    CosmosDBEmulatorContainer cosmosDB() {
        return new CosmosDBEmulatorContainer("mcr.microsoft.com/cosmosdb/linux/azure-cosmos-emulator:vnext-preview")
                .withReuse(true);
    }
}

// Integration base class
@SpringBootTest
@Import(TestInfraConfig.class)
@Testcontainers
abstract class AbstractCellHealthIT {
    // shared wiring — all IT classes extend this
}
```

### 14d. `@ParameterizedClass` (JUnit 6) — parameterize entire test classes

JUnit 6 introduces `@ParameterizedClass` to run a whole class with different inputs:

```java
@ParameterizedClass
@ValueSource(strings = {"cell-us-east-01", "cell-eu-west-01", "cell-ap-southeast-01"})
class MultiCellAggregationTest {

    @Parameter
    String cellId;

    @MockitoBean ICellHealthAggregatorService aggregatorService;

    @Test
    void aggregatesHealthForEachCell() {
        when(aggregatorService.aggregate(cellId)).thenReturn(CellHealthFixtures.healthyCell());
        assertThat(aggregatorService.aggregate(cellId).status()).isEqualTo("UP");
    }
}
```

### 14e. Spring Framework 7 context caching — `@Nested` hierarchy note

`SpringExtension` now uses **test-method scope** for `ExtensionContext`. If `@Nested` tests inside
a `@SpringBootTest` class lose injected beans between outer/inner class boundaries, annotate the
top-level class:

```java
@SpringBootTest
@SpringExtensionConfig(useTestClassScopedExtensionContext = true)
class CellHealthServiceIT {

    @Autowired ICellHealthAggregatorService service;

    @Nested class WhenCriticalDepDown { /* inherits context correctly */ }
    @Nested class WhenAllHealthy      { /* inherits context correctly */ }
}
```

### 14f. Anti-patterns — what NOT to do

```java
// BAD — @MockBean is REMOVED in Spring Boot 4 (causes NoSuchBeanDefinitionException)
@MockBean private SomeService svc;                     // use @MockitoBean

// BAD — missing MockitoExtension; mocks won't be initialized in Boot 4
class FooTest {
    @Mock SomeDep dep;                                  // NPE at runtime
    // add @ExtendWith(MockitoExtension.class)
}

// BAD — JUnit assertEquals; switch to AssertJ assertThat for richer messages
assertEquals(200, response.getStatusCode().value());

// BAD — addFilters = false hides security misconfigurations
mockMvc = MockMvcBuilders.standaloneSetup(controller).addFilters().build();

// BAD — Testcontainers 1.x module name (does not resolve in TC 2.0)
testImplementation("org.testcontainers:postgresql")   // use testcontainers-postgresql

// BAD — new instance per test pollutes context cache; use @TestConfiguration
@SpringBootTest
class FooIT {
    @Container PostgreSQLContainer<?> db = new PostgreSQLContainer<>("postgres:16");
}
```

## 15. Do NOT — recurring review findings (build-enforced)

These anti-patterns were re-flagged across multiple reviews. They are now enforced by
`ArchitectureRulesTest` (ArchUnit) and JaCoCo so violations fail the build, not just review.
Do not reintroduce them.

| # | Do NOT | Do instead | Enforcement |
|---|--------|-----------|-------------|
| 1 | Call external cloud SDKs (`com.azure..`, AWS, etc.) from `..controllers..` | Keep controllers thin; put SDK calls in the service layer | ArchUnit `controllersMustNotDependOnExternalCloudSdks` |
| 2 | Use a `private static` field set via `@Autowired` (static service locator) | Constructor-inject an instance `@Component` | ArchUnit `mainCodeMustNotUseMutableStaticFields` (static fields must be `final`) |
| 3 | Assert with JUnit `Assertions.*` (`assertEquals`, `assertTrue`) | Use AssertJ `assertThat(...)` | ArchUnit `testsMustUseAssertJNotJUnitAssertions` |
| 4 | Pin a dependency the Spring Boot BOM already manages (e.g. `commons-lang3:3.x`) | Declare it version-less; pin only non-BOM libs (e.g. `commons-collections4`) | code review |
| 5 | Read config via method-param `@Value` for related settings | Bind a `@Validated @ConfigurationProperties` **record** with `@DefaultValue` + `@Positive` | code review |
| 6 | Initialize constant path lists with `new ArrayList<>(Arrays.asList(...))` | Use immutable `List.of(...)` | code review |
| 7 | Expose `/actuator/**` (incl. `/actuator/prometheus`) unauthenticated | Permit only `/actuator/health/**` + `/actuator/info`; keep metrics authenticated | code review |
| 8 | Hardcode the API version in `OpenApiConfig` | Externalize to `cdp.api.version` in `application.yml` and inject via `@Value` | code review |
| 9 | Build error responses as bare strings or per-handler maps | Route every handler through `ExceptionUtils.buildErrorResponse(...)` returning `ApiErrorResponseDTO` with i18n keys from `ErrorMessageConstants` | code review |
| 10 | Leak exception messages / resource paths to clients | Return only generic i18n messages; log details server-side | code review |
| 11 | Drop duplicate validation keys silently (`(a,b) -> a`) | Merge by concatenation (`a + "; " + b`) | code review |
| 12 | Register MDC/correlation filters at default order | `@Order(Ordered.HIGHEST_PRECEDENCE)` and `MDC.clear()` in `finally` (virtual-thread safe) | code review |
| 13 | `new RecordDTO(...)` with many args in services/mappers | MapStruct `@Mapping` variant methods or dedicated mapper | code review |
| 14 | Inline package names in signatures (`com.example.app...HealthStatus`) | Normal imports | code review |
| 15 | Short injected names (`mapper`, `service`) | Descriptive names matching type (`cellHealthEventMapper`) | code review |
| 16 | Hardcoded `@Scheduled(fixedDelayString = "15000")` | Property placeholder `${cdp...}` + yaml + constant default | code review |
| 17 | Hardcoded path strings in controllers (`"/events"`, `"/stream"`) | `ApiConstants` segments | code review |
| 18 | String-matching HTTP codes in exception messages (`contains("429")`) | `HttpStatus` / SDK `getStatusCode()` | code review |
| 19 | Stub `IHealthProbe` bean that throws on use | Factory that builds real probe instances (`PeerProbeFactory`) | code review |
| 20 | Duplicate `RestClient` beans with different timeout sources | Single bean from `RestClientProperties` | code review |
| 21 | Raw `Caffeine.newBuilder()` or `private final Cache<>` / `ConcurrentHashMap` fields on `@Service`/`@Repository` production beans | `@EnableCaching` + yaml spec; sole owner `CellHealthCacheService` with `@Cacheable`/`@CacheEvict`; test/local in-memory stores `@Profile("local","test")` only | ArchUnit `productionBeansMustNotDeclareMutableCollectionFields` |
| 22 | Repeat `optional.orElseThrow(() -> new EntityNotFoundException(...))` in controllers | Add `require*` / `read*ById` on the service that delegates to cached `find*`; controller calls the throwing method (§7) | code review |
| 23 | Throw inside `@Cacheable` when negative caching of misses is required | Keep `@Cacheable` on `find*` returning `Optional`; add non-cached `require*` wrapper | code review |

## 16. Health / probe patterns (your service reference)

| Pattern | Rule |
|---------|------|
| Dynamic probes | Use a `@Component` factory (`PeerProbeFactory`) that returns probe instances; never register a stub bean that throws `UnsupportedOperationException` |
| HTTP status detection | Use `HttpStatus.TOO_MANY_REQUESTS.value()` or SDK `getStatusCode()` + `instanceof` — never `ex.getMessage().contains("429")` |
| Probe detail strings | i18n via `ProbeMessageResolver` + `messages.properties`; log full exception at ERROR, return resolved message to rollup |
| Executor lifecycle | Custom `ExecutorService` beans need `@PreDestroy shutdown()`; cancel in-flight futures when deadlines expire |
| Micrometer gauges | Hold mutable values in `AtomicInteger`/`AtomicLong` registered once — do not call `meterRegistry.gauge(name, primitive)` on every update |
| Statelessness | Horizontally scalable production beans must **not** declare class-level `Map`/`List`/`Set`/`Queue`/`Cache` fields. Shared durable state → Cosmos/Event Hub SDK. Ephemeral read cache → Spring `CacheManager` via centralized `CellHealthCacheService` (`@Cacheable`/`@CacheEvict`). SSE connections → `SseEmitterRegistry`. In-memory repos/consumers are `@Profile("local")` / `@Profile("test")` only |
| Control-plane scope | Cell-type–gated probe lists (infra always; peer services only for `controlplane` cells); real actuator indicators live in peer repos (separate Jira, e.g. PROJ-123) |

### Enforcement mechanism

- `src/test/java/com/gm/cdp/architecture/ArchitectureRulesTest.java` — ArchUnit rules above.
- `build.gradle.kts` — JaCoCo measures `configuration` + `dto` packages (0.80 line gate); Lombok-generated
  members are excluded via `lombok.config` (`lombok.addLombokGeneratedAnnotation = true`).
- Keep demo/scaffold controllers and services **out** of the repo; they are an anti-pattern factory.
